observations.recommendation:
We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of its road networks in order to ascertain the existence of the balance of the Road Networks account;
Direct the Municipal Engineer to provide the Municipal Accountant and the GSO with the complete description and cost segregation of the road networks to facilitate the preparation of the subsidiary ledgers for roads and its components;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to prepare maintain or submit to the audit team the Local Road Network Ledger Card, schedule or subsidiary records for roads and road components for every road network and the corresponding lapsing schedule for the computation of the depreciation for each component at the end of the year;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to disclose in the notes to FS the total road network system of the LGU in accordance with the proper disclosure prescribed in COA Circular No. 2015-008; and
Require the General Services Officer to prepare and maintain the Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components, including Road Map. A Report on Local Road Network is to be prepared by the General Services Officer at the end of accounting period.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Stop the petty cash fund maintained by the elected officer for the petty operating expenses of the SBO and refrain from designating elected officials as disbursing officers, in accordance with the requirements of COA Circular No. 97-002;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that all PCF granted were correctly handled under the general principles of the imprest system and to strictly maintain the PCF according to the authorized amount;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to correctly record the PCF in the books and its replenishments in accordance with the journal entries required in the MNGAS for LGUs and make the necessary adjusting entries to correct any error in the books, if any;
Require the AOs to record daily all the transactions in the prescribed cashbook and submit all supporting documents together with the completely filled up PCVs. Require both the AO and the accountant to reconcile their books of accounts at least quarterly;
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to require all AOs to fully liquidate all the PCF at the end of the year and to return any unused cash within twenty (20) days after the end of the year;
Require the Municipal Accountant to properly monitor all cash advances and ensure that all cash advances for a particular year are not used to pay expenses of prior period or other years;
Reduce the AO’s PCF to an amount sufficient only for one month’s requirement of the MSWDO and SBO/VMO based on the average monthly disbursements; and
Require the AOs to request replenishment when the disbursements reach at least 75%, or as the need requires, by submitting a replenishment voucher with all supporting documents duly summarized in a report of disbursements.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Require the MEEDO to submit the Memorandum of Agreement (MOA) of the LGU with the Kauswagan Community Multi-Purpose Cooperative (KCMPCO) and the contract over the management and operational control of dormitories/hotel and rental payment of cafeteria/restaurant building, along with all other necessary documents;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to submit the Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) as verification for the recording of revenue from the contract of dormitories/hotels and rental of the cafeteria/restaurant building;
Direct the MEEDO to submit a Statement of Account of the private owner in KIOCC to the audit team for audit verifications, and ensure their office closely monitors all collections related to Local Economic Enterprises (LEE); and
Direct the MEEDO to prepare feasibility study and detailed business plans in all of the LGU’s Local Economic Enterprises in accordance with the Manual on the Setting Up and Operation of Local Economic Enterprises of 2016.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Submit a copy of the ordinance/s duly stamped “Received” by the province to establish the authority over the disbursements made to the contracts paid through the “supplemental” and “realigned” funds, and to ascertain the propriety of the transactions in order to avoid any possible disallowances thereof;
Ensure that all supplemental and realignments of the ensuing period from here on be supported with a copy of the ordinance duly stamped “Received” by the province, exhibiting the new revenue sources or the original source of fund from where the augmentation should come from, and in compliance with the requirements of Sections 305 (a), 321 and 336 of Republic Act No. 7160; and
Require the Municipal Budget Officer to submit a summary report of all supplemental and realigned funds of CY 2023 indicating therein the following:
Ordinance issued, if any, authorizing the Local Chief Executive or the Presiding Officer to augment any item;
the SB Resolution;
the original sources of fund, specify the new revenue sources for supplemental fund and for realignments identify the unimplemented project or item in the original budget from where the augmentation should come from, which should be savings in other items within the same expense class of each office’s respective appropriations;
the purpose for which the fund was realigned or where it was utilized; and
the amount of supplemental or realigned funds.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive instruct the GSO to:
Provide adequate ventilation at the storage area with the end view of ensuring that items with special storage conditions are considered;
Implement proper handling and storage of all properties by providing shelves, establishing a piling system; proper classification/segregation and labeling of items;
Ensure proper maintenance and good housekeeping of the warehouse; and
Maintain records, books, reports, and stock cards to provide accurate and complete information.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive:
Comply all the lacking documents and other deficiencies noted for each contract;
Properly complete all the necessary information that was left blank for each document submitted;
Reduce the bidding documents to items necessary only to the procurements and incorporate as part of the document any technical specifications of the procurements, including plans, drawings, and engineering details, if any;
Submit the correct ABC in all the procurements of the Municipality;
Ensure that contractor indicates the date of receipt in all the notices and documents received by them and ensure as well that the person signing the contract and all its integral parts is legally authorized by the contract supported with Special Power of Attorney, Board/Partnership Resolution, or Secretary’s Certificate, whichever is applicable;
Properly conduct the bid evaluation and post-qualification based on the process provided for in RA 9184 and its revised IRR and truthfully prepare the reports based only on the actual conduct of bid evaluation and post-qualification;
Require the winning bidder to post the necessary Performance Bond/ Security prior to the signing of the contract;
Provide a written explanation of the discussed contracts that were awarded despite the legal inconsistencies with the laws, rules, and regulations governing the government procurement;
Require the BAC to revisit and comply with the provisions of RA 9184 and its revised IRR and all the issuances of the GPPB as well as constantly update themselves with any new guidelines;
Submit contracts not yet submitted to COA for review; and
Revisit the composition of the BAC and make necessary changes, if warranted.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to submit the liquidation reports to the Municipal Accounting Office;
Consider the designation of a Special Disbursing Officer (SDO) other than the Municipal Treasurer to lessen his cash advances accountability and to effectively monitor the grant and liquidation of each cash advance.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking documents;
The Sangguniang Bayan to include in the SB resolution the legal basis of land acquisition and its valuation, otherwise, the purchase of lot will fall under unnecessary expenses;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to submit the CAF amounting to P300 million for the purchase of land from Mr. Teodorico H. Pacaldo; and
Require the Local Chief Executive and Dep Ed official to submit an explanation for utilizing the SEF funds for the purchase of land from Mr. Pacaldo.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Require the Municipal Accountant to submit the legal basis relative to the grant of EWA;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to ensure the correct usage of accounts for payment of bonuses and allowances pursuant to the NGAS/GAM.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Require the Municipal Accountant to stop the payment of honorarium for observers and undertake necessary actions for the refund;
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that claims for BAC honorarium are completely supported with attendance sheet, certification that the procurement involves competitive bidding, notice of award and minutes of BAC Meeting.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that future procurement on motor vehicles be covered with warranty security either in the form of retention money or special bank guarantee in an amount equivalent to one percent (1%) of the purchase price;
Instruct the Bids and Awards Committee to prepare contract for every procurement; to require the winning bidders the posting of performance security; and to conduct the pre bid conference, if warranted.

We recommended and management agreed that the Local Chief Executive undertake the following:
Direct the Municipal Treasurer to provide an explanation for his preparation of check no. 72349303 on August 8, 2021 despite the non-delivery of the water tankers at that time in the LGU;
Comply with all the lacking documents and direct the BAC to explain other deficiencies noted for each contract;
Complete the necessary information that were left blank for each document submitted; and
Reduce the copied form of bidding documents to items necessary only to the procurements and incorporate as part of the document any specifications of the procurements.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Direct the BAC Secretariat to ensure that PPMPs are properly evaluated in a manner that procurement activities can be synchronized and that PPMPs of all offices/departments were consolidated in the APP taking into consideration their budget framework, priorities and availability of funds;
Instruct the GSO to adopt the procurement activities and timelines as reflected in the APP.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to submit the following documents for each project (a) Inspection Report by the Agency’s Authorized Engineer, (b) Statement of Time Elapsed, (c) Monthly Certificate of Payment, (d) Contractor’s Affidavit on payment of laborers and materials;
Require the Municipal Accountant to ensure that prospective payments for progress billings are supported with complete documents to establish the propriety of the transactions.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Direct the Municipal Accountant to submit the lacking documents;
Instruct the Local School Board and Municipal Budget Officer to stop charging security expenses which are not attributable in the activities of DepEd against SEF funds pursuant with the Dep ED-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Require the Municipal Treasurer and the Municipal Accountant to release the shares from RPT to the barangays on a quarterly basis within five (5) days after the end of each quarter;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to prepare the necessary adjusting entries to recognize in the books the ₱20 million amount of land.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to submit the DTRs and copies of contracts for CY 2021 transactions;
Require the JOs to prepare and submit the required DTR and accomplishment report as attachment to the payrolls prospectively.

We recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:
Direct the Local Chief Executive to ensure timely implementation of projects;
Require the MPDO to provide specific target dates of implementation of the PPAs and the related target schedule for each procurement activities in order to ensure timely implementation.

We have recommended to the Municipal Treasurer to:

Restrict access to cash accountable forms and their records to authorized personnel only to reduce the risk of unauthorized use and/or loss to the government;

Strictly implement the procedures on the requisitions of accountable forms and daily turnover of collections to strengthen the Municipality’s control over collections;

See to it that all collectors are properly supervised and their accountabilities are regularly monitored; and

Require the erring accountable officer to remit the collections, and record, update and submit the cashbooks, RCD/RCR to COA, if issued; to present the missing accountable forms to COA, if unissued; or to give notices of loss in accordance of COA Circular no. 84-233 dated August 21, 1984.

We have recommended to the LCE the following:

Instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to conduct regular reconciliation of the cashbook and subsidiary/general ledger balances to ensure completeness and accuracy of the recorded transactions and balance of cash in bank accounts;

Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to identify the items for adjustments and correct their records based on the monthly bank reconciliation statements made supported with copies of bank debit and credit memoranda secured from the depository banks;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to monitor each bank account to avoid it becoming dormant, to close the bank accounts with dormant deposits and to make the necessary adjustments to revert the balances of these closed accounts from the Special Trust Fund to the General Fund or refund to the source agency, if necessary; and 

Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to perform the required procedures in the immediate destruction of obsolete checks in order to eliminate accountability of the accountable officer over the checks no longer needed in the operations of the Municipality.

We have recommended the following:

The Local Chief Executive to recommend the budget officer to attend training that involved budgeting;

The Municipal Budget Officer to maintain the required registries of funds / appropriations / allotments and obligations and utilization in order to avoid juggling of funds and for internal control purposes. Also, to facilitate the realization of the programs / projects / activities embodied in the Approved Annual Budget;

Submit the quarterly report statement of Allotment, Obligations and Balances and monthly the registries; and

Strict adherence to the provision of laws, rules and regulations.

We have recommended to the Municipal Accountant the following:

To suspend or withhold from the salaries of officials and employees the amount corresponding to their unsettled cash advances;

To follow up from the grantees the submission of their liquidation documents;

To stop the practice of granting additional cash advances to those with unliquidated travel expenses vouchers;

Otherwise, appropriate disciplinary measures shall be imposed against them should they continue to violate Section 89 of PD 1445.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive the following:

Require the Municipal Budget Officer to augment funds for the titling of the parcels of land enumerated in the inventory of lands;

Require the Municipal Assessor to coordinate with the General Services Officer in providing the lacking documents needed in the titling of the land; 

Direct the Municipal Assessor to prioritize the registration and the transfer of title of the land to the Municipality of Kauswagan; and

Municipal Accountant to ensure land should be properly recorded in the books of accounts and secure deed of donations or deed of sale as basis in the titling and in the recording.

We have recommended the following:

Install roving personnel who will be a lookout of the project to avoid being cut or burned by unknown individuals;

Cause the repair of all defects noted and submit a complete report on the same to the Audit Team.

Enforce strict supervision on the implementation of infrastructure projects to ensure good quality of work and to avoid defects;

Make sure that all water supply system projects comply with the requirement on quality test for water, pursuant to DPWH Department Order No. 102 dated May 27, 2016;

Planning Section conducts survey and investigations in accordance with the criteria and standards adopted by the agency to carry out accurate design and effective production of plans. They should first consider series of meeting in the community in order to ensure immediate implementation of the project when the funds are downloaded;

Municipal Engineer to constantly monitor the projects implemented if the projects were effectively used.

Submit the quarterly status of the projects implemented.

We have recommended to the Local Chief Executive the following:

In view of the computerization of the Commission on Audit in monitoring audit suspensions, disallowances and charges, to assign specific personnel to do the compliance of supporting documents and monitoring of it. Otherwise, after the ninety (90) day period of non-compliance, the system will automatically lapsed, notice of disallowance will immediately be required to the audit team for issuance;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to pre-audit all claims or disbursement of funds and require complete supporting documents before finally paying the claims and affix her signature to the Disbursement Vouchers before submission to the audit team to minimize audit suspensions.

We recommended the following:

The General Service Officer to complete the conduct of actual physical inventory with the committee to arrive at an accurate balance; to prepare a separate report on unserviceable properties, plant and equipment and facilitate the preparation of Inspection and Inventory Report; and to furnish the Audit Team with copy of the updated Inventory Report;

The Municipal Accountant to make the necessary adjustments on the deficiencies noted on the accounts property, plant and equipment based on the result of the actual inventory taking and reconcile with the accounting records. Also, to review the computed Accumulated Depreciation to determined its proper computation.

We recommended to the Head of the Human Resource Management Office:

To submit the contract of service of the job orders and consultants with specific duties and functions;

To forward the approved contract of services of the consultants together with supporting document as enumerated in COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012; and; 

To reconcile her manpower complement based on the actual manpower.

We recommended the following:

The Municipal Treasurer to conduct a reconciliation of their accounts with the accounting records every month;

Also, the Municipal Accountant to prepare and submit to COA the monthly ledgers for timely monitoring and evaluation of accounts.

We have recommended to the LCE the following:
Instruct the Municipal Accountant and Municipal Treasurer to conduct regular reconciliation of the cashbook and subsidiary/general ledger balances to ensure completeness and accuracy of the recorded transactions and balance of cash in bank accounts;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to identify the items for adjustments and correct their records based on the monthly bank reconciliation statements made supported with copies of bank debit and credit memoranda secured from the depository banks;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to monitor each bank account to avoid it becoming dormant, to close the bank accounts with dormant deposits and to make the necessary adjustments to revert the balances of these closed accounts from the Special Trust Fund to the General Fund or refund to the source agency, if necessary; and
Instruct the Municipal Treasurer to perform the required procedures in the immediate destruction of obsolete checks in order to eliminate accountability of the accountable officer over the checks no longer needed in the operations of the Municipality.

We have recommended that the Local Chief Executive the following:
Require the Municipal Budget Officer to augment funds for the titling of the parcels of land enumerated in the inventory of lands;
Require the Municipal Assessor to coordinate with the General Services Officer in providing the lacking documents needed in the titling of the land;
Direct the Municipal Assessor to prioritize the registration and the transfer of title of the land to the Municipality of Kauswagan; and
Municipal Accountant to ensure land should be properly recorded in the books of accounts and secure deed of donations or deed of sale as basis in the titling and in the recording.

We recommended to the Head of the Human Resource Management Office:
a. To submit the contract of service of the job orders and consultants with specific duties and functions;
b. To forward the approved contract of services of the consultants together with supporting document as enumerated in COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012; and; 
c. To reconcile her manpower complement based on the actual manpower.

Recommendations:
We recommended to the Head of the Human Resource Management Office:
To submit the contract of service of the job orders and consultants with specific duties and functions;
To forward the approved contract of services of the consultants together with supporting document as enumerated in COA Circular 2012-001 dated June 14, 2012; and; 
To reconcile her manpower complement based on the actual manpower.
The agency committed to comply with the above provision of rules and regulations. Towards this, the team shall undertake periodic monitoring.

We have recommended the following:
a. Local Chief Executive in coordination with the Sangguniang Bayan, adopt and implement clear and reasonable policies concerning the payment of mobile expenses. The guidelines should include at least the following:
i. Officers and employees who will be allowed to claim reimbursements of mobile expenses, together with the justifications why they are allowed;
ii. Mode of Payments and required supporting documents;
iii. Mobile expense limit;
iv. Accounting treatment of any complimentary cellphone units.
b. Municipal Mayor to issue an office order providing a monthly limit of load allowance and that any amount exceeding the ceiling provided to officials and employees shall be charged against the user through salary deduction.
c. In the statement of account, attached the call logs showing the names and remarks as official or personal calls.
d. Terminate excessive globe plans. Maintain only one mobile account.

We have recommended the following:
Local Chief Executive in coordination with the Sangguniang Bayan, adopt and implement clear and reasonable policies concerning the payment of mobile expenses. The guidelines should include at least the following:
Officers and employees who will be allowed to claim reimbursements of mobile expenses, together with the justifications why they are allowed;
Mode of Payments and required supporting documents;
Mobile expense limit;
Accounting treatment of any complimentary cellphone units.
Municipal Mayor to issue an office order providing a monthly limit of load allowance and that any amount exceeding the ceiling provided to officials and employees shall be charged against the user through salary deduction.
In the statement of account, attached the call logs showing the names and remarks as official or personal calls.
Terminate excessive globe plans. Maintain only one mobile account.
The agency committed to comply with the above provision of rules and regulations. Towards this, the team shall undertake periodic monitoring.

We have recommended the following:
a. All collectors should remit collections intact and daily to the Liquidating Officer; 
b. The Liquidating Officer should then deposit intact daily all the collections to authorized government depository bank; 
c. Prepare and submit the Report on Collections and Deposits (RCD) in accordance with the instructions in filling up the RCD Form; and
d. The Municipal Treasurer should submit a report showing the breakdown of the deposits made and identifying to which collections or fund transfers these deposits pertain. Submit the same within 15 days from receipt hereof.

We have recommended to all Accountable Officers under Municipal Treasurer’s Office:
a. To accomplish properly the Report of Collections and Deposit;
b. To maintain a cashbook for each accountable form and each type of fund;
c. To record daily her collections in the cashbook in ink and in the order they occur;
d. To balance, rule and close at the end of the day her cashbook and foot and close the books at the end of each month.
e. To reconcile her records with the accounting at least at the end of each quarter. 
f. We have also recommended to the Accounting Office to create a subsidiary ledger for each collecting officer.

We have recommended the following:
a. The Municipal Treasurer and the Revenue Collector should reinstitute immediately the missing funds;
b. The Municipal Mayor should recommend for the relief of the Accountable Officer from her treasury and collection functions and may assign her to other work assignment not involving money and property accountabilities; 
c. Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the monthly balances of debits and credits to the account Cash in Vault and submit the monthly reconciliation to the Audit Team Leader for verification;
d. Institute appropriate administrative and/or criminal charges against the Accountable Officers for malversation of public funds pursuant to Article 217 of the Revised Penal Code; 
e. Require the incoming Municipal Treasurer to install internal control measures to ensure that all collections be remitted / deposited intact and daily; and
f. All disbursements should have appropriation and properly disbursed with complete supporting documents.

Recommendations:
We have recommended the following:
All collectors should remit collections intact and daily to the Liquidating Officer;
The Liquidating Officer should then deposit intact daily all the collections to authorized government depository bank;
Prepare and submit the Report on Collections and Deposits (RCD) in accordance with the instructions in filling up the RCD Form; and
The Municipal Treasurer should submit a report showing the breakdown of the deposits made and identifying to which collections or fund transfers these deposits pertain. Submit the same within 15 days from receipt hereof.

Recommendations:
We have recommended to all Accountable Officers under Municipal Treasurer’s Office:
To accomplish properly the Report of Collections and Deposit;
To maintain a cashbook for each accountable form and each type of fund;
To record daily her collections in the cashbook in ink and in the order they occur;
To balance, rule and close at the end of the day her cashbook and foot and close the books at the end of each month.
To reconcile her records with the accounting at least at the end of each quarter.
We have also recommended to the Accounting Office to create a subsidiary ledger for each collecting officer.

Recommendations:
We have recommended the following:
The Municipal Treasurer and the Revenue Collector should reinstitute immediately the missing funds;
The Municipal Mayor should recommend for the relief of the Accountable Officer from her treasury and collection functions and may assign her to other work assignment not involving money and property accountabilities;
Direct the Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer to reconcile the monthly balances of debits and credits to the account Cash in Vault and submit the monthly reconciliation to  the Audit Team Leader for verification;
Institute appropriate administrative and/or criminal charges against the Accountable Officers for malversation of public funds pursuant to Article 217 of the Revised Penal Code;
Require the incoming Municipal Treasurer to install internal control measures to ensure that all collections be remitted /deposited intact and daily; and
All disbursements should have appropriation and properly disbursed with complete supporting documents.
